[Thank you to A. Dodds for this update on a continuing story. The
outbreak in Idaho was reported as pale cyst nematode _Globodera
pallida_. This nematode may cause crop losses as high as 70 percent
under poor management and it is classed as a very high risk to potato
producing areas. Spread occurs via soil, plant debris and infected
potato tubers. Potato golden cyst nematode (_Globodera
rostochiensis_) has a similarly high impact. It is spread in much the
same way but so far occurs only at a few sites in North America.
A worldwide distribution of pale cyst nematode map is at:
<http://www.eppo.org/QUARANTINE/nematodes/Globodera_pallida/HETDPA_map. htm>
A worldwide distribution of golden cyst nematode map is at:
<http://www.eppo.org/QUARANTINE/nematodes/Globodera_rostochiensis/HETDRO
_map.htm>
A phptograph showing cysts is at:
<http://www.niab.com/jdd/public/images/pcn-pop1.jpg>
A picture of nematodes is at:
<http://zeldia.cap.ed.ac.uk/nematodeESTs/species/GPC.jpg>
Pictures of field symptoms on potato are shown at:
<http://www.dowagro.com/uk/images/PCN-damage-potatoes.jpg>, and at:
<http://www.dpi.vic.gov.au/CA25677D007DC87D/LUbyDesc/Ag0572a/$File/Ag057
2a.jpg>
Information on _Globodera pallida_ is available at:
<http://nematode.unl.edu/pest5.htm>, and at:
<http://plpnemweb.ucdavis.edu/nemaplex/taxadata/G053S1.HTM>
- Mod.DHA]
